nglish <i>cirice</i> ‘church’) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kerton","meanings":["English (Somerset):","variant of   Kirton  .","variant of   Cureton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Kirton was born in 1450, his father, John Kryton, was 61 and his mother, Margaret Hulse, was 35. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Margery Milborne."},"et":{"1450–":"1450–Surnud","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1455–1512":"1455–1512","–Female":"Surnud","1474–1529":"1474–1529","–1549":"–1549","1390–1459":"1390–1459","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1415":"1415","1459":"1459","1457":"1457","1512":"1512","1455":"1455","Abt 1474":"umbes 1474","1474":"1474","1450":"1450","1529":"1529","1390":"1390","1549":"1549","Southwark, Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Southwark, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Edmonton, Middlesex, England":"Edmonton, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1450–":"1450–Kuollut","1450–Male":"1450–Kuollut","1455–1512":"1455–1512","–Female":"Kuollut","1474–1529":"1474–1529","–1549":"–1549","1390–1459":"1390–1459","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1415":"1415","1459":"1459","1457":"1457","1512":"1512","1455":"1455","Abt 1474":"noin 1474","1474":"1474","1450":"1450","1529":"1529","1390":"1390","15